# 🔹 Are these methods compulsory to override?

## ✔ 1. Abstract methods (normal interface methods)

```java
interface A {
    void m1();
}
```

👉 **Compulsory to override ✅**

* If a class implements `A`, it **must implement `m1()`**
* Otherwise → compilation error

---

## ✔ 2. Default methods (Java 8)

```java
default void m2() {
    System.out.println("Default method");
}
```

👉 **Optional to override ❌ (your choice)**

### Why?

* Already has implementation
* Class can:

  * Use it as it is ✅
  * OR override it ✅

---

## ✔ 3. Static methods (Java 8)

```java
static void m3() {
    System.out.println("Static method");
}
```

👉 **Cannot be overridden ❌**

### Why?

* Belongs to interface, not object
* Called like:

  ```
  A.m3();
  ```

---

## ✔ 4. Private methods (Java 9)

```java
private void helper() { }
```

👉 **Not accessible outside ❌**

* Cannot be overridden
* Only used inside interface

---

# 🔹 Final Table (Very Important 💯)

| Method Type | Override Required? | Reason               |
| ----------- | ------------------ | -------------------- |
| Abstract    | ✅ Yes              | No body              |
| Default     | ❌ Optional         | Already has body     |
| Static      | ❌ Not allowed      | Belongs to interface |
| Private     | ❌ Not allowed      | Internal use only    |

---

# 🔹 Key Understanding (Interview Level 🔥)

> Only abstract methods force implementation.
> Default methods give flexibility.
> Static and private methods are not part of class contract.

---

# 🔹 One-line Answer 💯

> “Only abstract methods are compulsory to override; default methods are optional, while static and private methods cannot be overridden.”

